		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P>Battleblade-Xegony wrote:<BR><I><B><BR></B></I>Knights have always been able to tank appropriate content. It just doesn't happen to be the same appropriate content a Warrior might tank.<BR><BR>Ya see you start out with a misrepresentation - that Knight tanking is intended to be the same as Warrior tanking. It isn't.<BR></P>
<P><FONT color=#3366ff>I never stated that Knight tanking should be the same as warrior tanking, I said warriors should tank better. Appropriately geared knights tanking group content that's balanced around their level of progression in no way makes knight tanking and warrior tanking the same. Warriors would have the ability to tank it with gear somewhat lower, but an endgame knight should be able to tank endgame group content reliably. The difference between warriors and Knights shouldn't be too large though in terms of tanking 10% dmg reduction for warriors is sufficient to ensure the usefulness of the class and downward scaling disciplines with enough group usefulness to compare to knight downward scaling abilities should be included in the package. That effectively allows warriors to tank content a tier before knights. CoA warrior would be roughly on the dps taking level of a demi knight.</FONT><BR><BR>Sure, there should be a couple of mobs needing to be pulled in every expansion, but that should be the exception not the rule. Players should rarely die and need a res, want clerical buffs when a Druid or Shaman is the group's mainhealer - mobs shouldn't debuff you and buffs should never wear off, or need a heal.<BR><BR>Don't you mean to say, the vast majority of content should give Knights Tank Parity (and Spellbook Superiority).<BR><BR><FONT color=#3366ff>You'd have a point if the inability to pull effectively robbed warriors of viability in the primary roll but seeing as it doesn't you are just blowing hot air. Inability to tank content makes knights a class without a primary role. No class can exist as a useful grouping class without a primary role they can perform adequately so your argument is nothing but saying knights shouldn't be useful in endgame group game.</FONT></P><FONT color=#3366ff></FONT><I><B>
<P><BR></P></B></I>That's what hard hitting <U>is</U> sir. Unmatched survivability means doing a bodycount. It's never meant <U>everyone</U> else dying. Even with GoD trials adjusted 5 levels too hard some Knights - wearing the previous expansion's gear TANKED (not stood there and watched a Ranger WS, but actually tanked) and won.<BR><BR>Should any group content be designed so only a small handful of Knights can manage it when it's first encountered? IMO 6 is too small a number, but 100 <U>might</U> be reasonable. Afterall, endgame raid content isn't exactly beaten by every Tom, **SMURF**, and Harry. Why should endgame group content be any different. The late bloomers will beat it sometime down the road if they persist. Heck, right now some guilds are just breaking into PoTime sir (I'm not belittling breaking into PoTime - those that do so have accomplished a major in-game milestone and we ALL salute you).<BR>
<P><FONT color=#3366ff>PoTime knights would be tanking PoTime level content, as a demiplane knight I expect to be tanking content tuned for demiplane groups should such content be implemented, simple as that. It might be&nbsp;difficult for me, but I'm not opposed to difficult as long as it's reasonably within my grasp.&nbsp;If content exists for knights at the post-demi level then great and if demi warriors are capable of jumping into it that's fine, but that has nothing to do with me being able to tank content that's designed for those around the same gear level as me.<BR></FONT></P>
<P></P>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
