		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div>Actually if you understood game mechanics and how real human beings
play, unmatched survivability in the group game means relative
efficiency with regards to the healer in question assuming they are the
sole player healing- not a body count, sure a paladin could patch heal,
an sk could lifetap, but if the priest is good enough they won't need
the knights to do so- a body count involves a healer letting you die and if they have any
degree of competence, they will do everything they can to stop that
from happening (oh it can happen, Im not saying it doesn't, but usually
those are silly deaths from silly mistakes). Note I'm saying healer and
priest here k~ (because its always been all 3). In times where this is
the case, the warrior has the unmatched survivability in terms of the
priest being able to heal against more mobs until downtime occurs- the
one universal PITA, and thats getting adjusted with TSS (Rashere confirmed this AGES ago). Downtime will still
happen but now us priests wont have to med for obscene amounts of time,
instead it should hopefully be but a handful of minutes. The warrior
still tanks more mobs until the priest needs to call "lom, need to
med"- this is factual reality, I shouldn't have to pull out a string of
threads where druids claim they are able to heal 3-4 bolvirk until lom
with say a knight tanking, and 6-8 with a warrior of equivalent
progression, or similar where the shaman is the MH (but funnily, those
threads seem rarer). <br>
<br>
Thanks to your said unmatched survivability, vs more challenging
content it is more possible for a priest to reach total efficiency
healing a warrior than it is to do so healing a knight (Total
Efficiency is where Mana used is &lt;= mana regained, you've made
mistakes with FT regenning per second so I'm being nice here to explain
it to you) Yeah perhaps it is masochism to want to solo heal as a
healer if you're having problems and you're not wanting the knight to
heal, but tell me, how do healers improve otherwise if they don't learn
from their mistakes? Ditto for paladins who heal more than they aggro
in groups... yeah, I've seen that, you'd probably cheer him on, because
he was playing "cleric with sword" mode whilst the "real cleric with
the sword" was getting the real heal aggro.<br>
<br>
It only ever is a body count on raids, where MT death doesn't mean a
wipe, and people can just recover. Don't mix the 2 they are similar but
by heck they aren't congruent.<br>
