			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Tornicade_IV wrote:<BR>
<DIV></DIV>Exp we are both fully aware the itemization changes from expansion&nbsp; to expansion. it would be nice to see a new set of class specific gear with the expansion<BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>Yes we may be fully aware, but where as it can be shown that expansion after expansion the war class had this ac advantage. It now does not where as knight ac has increased with each expansion War ac the gap has been marginilized. There have been many comments in response to the OP's proposition, whom isnt even a warrior.</P>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Tornicade_IV wrote:&nbsp; page 7 reply 173</P>
<DIV>
<P>warrior do have an ac advanatage... shadowknights cant make them equip the ac.... hmm maybe there is a reason they dont equip the ac and shadowknights do?</P>
<P>on eqrankings the top 100 authenticated in hp is 88 warriors&nbsp; 3 sk's 9 paladins&nbsp; with the top pally ringing in at 45</P>
<P>top 100 authenticated in Ac is 27 warriors&nbsp; 46 sk's&nbsp; 27 Paladins.&nbsp; which i am guessing your rant about ac stems from. taking a closer look&nbsp;&nbsp; on eqrankings authenticate&nbsp; 365 players with 3000 plus ac.&nbsp;&nbsp; 95 ar sk's 109 are paladins and 161 are warriors</P>
<P>looking at the same pool of players&nbsp; hp we have 17 sk 58 paladins and 227 warriors with 14k + HP</P>
<P>of the 472 authentic players with 35+ shielding 99 are paladins&nbsp; 80 Sk's 256 Warriors&nbsp; 7 clerics and a couple other classes make up the remaining</P>
<P>of this sample &nbsp;399 have epic 2.0 for the warior class. 175 sk with epic 2.o&nbsp; 189 Paladins</P>
<P>You can argue the numbers all you wont but your nt gonn find a larger&nbsp; random sample</P></DIV>
<P></P>
<HR>

<P>But from looking at your response and the evidence we can see a few things.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ccffff>warrior do have an ac advanatage</FONT>, actually we may have a better multiplier but we do not have an advantage of more than a few ac on base items.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ccffff>shadowknights cant make them equip the ac.... hmm maybe there is a reason they dont equip the ac and shadowknights do?which i am guessing your rant about ac stems from. taking a closer look&nbsp;&nbsp; on eqrankings authenticate&nbsp; 365 players with 3000 plus ac.&nbsp;&nbsp; 95 ar sk's 109 are paladins and 161 are warriors.You can argue the numbers all you wont but your not gonna find a larger&nbsp; random sample.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#cccccc>Just looking at Breastplates alone it is evident that should the same gap had remained as it did thru POP/GATES which was about 13-14AC then its in essence a AC aug removed. Once COA BP are achieved the differences are 5ac/5hp id say thats a good refernce point. Itemization we can say is all screwed up and yes Id agree with that, doesnt change facts though. Whether the itemization guy favored another class or fell asleep at the wheel there was a traditional small margin of difference in the relative AC of items.</FONT></P>
<P>And the difference is that each of those 2 classes here have different idea's they gear for in a raid.A SHD wants clean consise regular damage for as low as possible. Even at max ac a raid named will still spike, there designed to do so as the spike damage is what usually kills you. Think we both know in&nbsp;group content a raider, even using there base ac off there items will still be higher ac than what the content was designed for generally.But looking at the past itemization we can also assume that history shows that wars generally had more AC in those items over other classes. So for them to gear for HP and make that a focus isnt that insane a premise.</P>
<P>So this is why I support the OP's idea here, because it does make sense. He put forth this idea to state that the relative difference's between the tank classes have caused a blurring, id say thats rather accurate. Where as I dont feel the DI increases would yield the results he was looking for, I do belive his assessment in AC is worth a look and possible itemization as since we are begining to all wear the same armor it is a way to ensure a slight class advantage which was always the case except in recent times. Whether you view this as class greed or not, id say its a rather fair assesment and doubtfull a more consise look could be done, but we could look at full numbers of the AC sets and count how many AC augments that would have been relativly naturally worn by such classes.</P>
<P>Placing in AC may not do anything great really, but it doesnt increase the effectivness of Defensive aswell as it doesnt remove a 1 round from a raid named so Id think of the 2 idea's projected 1 would be favored by knight classes over the other. But to say neither idea has merit, Isnt exactly a fair assesment its more of just wanting to retain what you might deem the new Knight advantage. AC</P>
<P>Chriten</P>	
