		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div><br><blockquote><hr>Sharbreena wrote:<br><div></div>
<p>Makeing group content challangeing is difficult for high end raiders because of the huge variance you have gearwise. I'm in the top 20 of sk's on my server gear wise, meaning&nbsp;I could prolly tank nearly any group scenario, push it to upper limits with me or high end warriors and it would lock out casuals. As&nbsp;I mentioned before, raiders raid for gear and stuff, grouping is more a hassle to grind for xp and aa's..or flags/keys. Grouping for many casuals is how they advance thier characters, so you couldn't make things too&nbsp; high end in the group format or it would leave them hanging.</p>
<p>You can't have a group level progression chart that would garner gear similar to high end raiders either or why bother raiding? That's the real balance point right now, how to get content that's challangeing for high end peeps with out being killer to casuals who don't have access to high end gear. That's why group mobs seem so lame to high end raiders, that's the bear minimum they could go and still make it doable for casuals.</p>
<p>Remember, casuals are locked out of raid zones predominatly allready, so they can't be locked out of group content cause that's thier only avenue&nbsp;for progression. If they can't progress either they will just stop playing, and those peeps eventually stop paying. So, it's not really a class issue so much as a style issue, raider vs casual. I have been both and believe me, there is a HUGE difference in what I can do now compared to what I could hope to do then.</p><br><hr></blockquote>I've been in the top 2, or, 3 on my server for a long time. However, we're a bit behind older servers.<br><br>&nbsp;When I progressed fully luclin and POP geared into ep's stuff hit hard. When we first got there a druid could not reliably keep me out with any kind of reasonable pull rate. Knights had very hard times with some named mobs, although, that changed pretty quickly with progression. There wasn't much gear for me on groupable mobs, or, maybe none. We were given plenty of reasons to go there though and group. Lots of our guildies with more moderate gear would get occasional upgrades, xp was good, zones were fun, there were drops that were interesting if not upgrades.<br><br>When we broke into GOD it was very hard to keep me up in places like Tipt, KT and even some work in Vxed hehe. Again, I needed a cleric, slower and even secondary healer at times. Knights had a tough time with named at first, but, they progressed through it. This occured again in MPG and RSS to a slightly lesser degree. I remember when we got to MPG and knights had a very tough time staying up as did any warriors with less progression than our 3 or 4 biggest fellows. tanking high dps nameds for them was much like BOT. they preffered having a warrior around. Clerics were mandatory at first etc.<br><br>They can do it, they have done it and I hope they will do it again. Group content challenge does not have to stop at some magic number. It should encompass players at all levels of progression. The best deal would be to retain significant RVR value so lower progression players would later utilize the same content as higher progression players.<br></div>	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
