		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div></div>Well as I said, overheal is inevitable no matter how you slice it, its
just how one manages how often the overheal occurs <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0> there are many
handy things I've learned from soloing, it really is funny but those
principles tie into raiding extremely well- the timing and frequency of
the heals, where you need to be efficient and not overheal else you
will go oom and fail and where you can't be the opposite else you/the
tank dies. When soloing its my deaths, when raiding its the tanks and
possibly more people, when all healers are oom, a raid wipes thats
inevitable. I try to teach the values I've learned, and they really do
help to minimise inefficiency and over healing, you can't make it
obsolete, but you can just reduce the chance of it happening, the drive
to be rigorously efficient is what makes the best healers imo.<br>
<br>
While I keep on preaching how his AC helps, I will say again that
whilst there are fights he is more suited for, there are many that the
hp warrior(s) that we have are suited for better, and the more balanced
ones (who tend to be more ac than hp) are the ones who I'd consider MT
certain things more than anything.<br>
<br>
Raids may be a bit skewed however, as unless I magically gain the dev's
eye to see what debuffs certain mobs have on them permanently, it will
be hard to say if a mob say Hatchet has attack debuffs permanently on
him, although knowing our druids they are good enough to make sure that
they never fade. But the data we have is the best we can give ) I'll ask
our ac freaks today in a few hours.<br>
